(529, 1, '2011-12-09 01:03:45', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'I did this for politics a while ago, thought it was time to address the bigger question.\r\n\r\nGrowing up, we went to <a href=\"http://www.northminster-indy.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Northminster Presbyterian Church</a> pretty regularly. My Mom was from a Presbyterian/Methodist background and my Dad was Southern Baptist (roughly). I\'m not sure how they ended up there, but I was baptized there, my mom worked there for a while and volunteered as well, I was active in the youth group (partially due to some awesome people: I\'m looking at you Ned, Traci, Amy, Grimmie, Stickle, Tami, McFarland, Loui, etc.)  I still remember my first real discussion with an honest-to-goodness atheist (Alan Federman) my freshman year in college and my incredulity that he could reject Jesus, let alone God.\r\n\r\nAs fate would have it, I was interested in Anthropology and didn\'t give much though to my job prospects, so I majored in it. In addition to the requirements, I padded my classes with Religious Studies, Sociology, Folklore and similar disciplines (the line between them is pretty blurry). I took a class in Buddhism and studied Taoism in my spare time. I appreciated my friend\'s \"Born Again Pagan\" T-shirt. All religions being equal, though the cool ones were exotic. And <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Tao-Physics-Exploration-Parallels-Anniversary/dp/1570625190\" target=\"_blank\">Taoism and physics</a> were identical.\r\n\r\nPoint being, I  can\'t pinpoint when I went from incredulity at doubting the Gospel to seriously doubting it myself, but it was somewhere in the late college years or soon thereafter (\'89-93).\r\n\r\nThe years 1993-2010 are difficult to describe. You could call them the lost (wilderness, to be biblical) years. The exotic lost its luster and I probably described myself as agnostic. I found it a little insensitive when \"God\" was mentioned at family gatherings. Around 2009, a co-worker (and friend) recommended going to her (I\'m thinking it\'s the Unitarian Universal) church. I responded by saying I was currently debating whether I was an Apatheist (not sure if there\'s a god or not, but trying to be a good person) or a Pretenditarian (not sure if there\'s a God, but pretending there is is often convenient).', 'My Religious History', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2011-12-09 01:03:45', '2011-12-09 01:03:45', '', 0, 'http://ttmsoia.andyhill.us/?p=529', 0, 'post', '', 0),
