(547, 1, '2012-01-13 23:52:22', '2012-01-13 23:52:22', 'I was talking with some co-workers about Voter ID laws after James O\'Keefe\'s latest escapade. I heard some very reasonable and astute criticisms of them. But we all agreed that we didn\'t know enough about the quantities of either unregistered voters or voter fraud (not to be confused with voter registration fraud, another issue.) I volunteered to do some research and email the results. The email is below. One item I failed to include is the Heritage Foundations\' (conservative think tank), <a href=\"http://www.heritage.org/research/reports/2011/08/without-proof-the-unpersuasive-case-against-voter-identification\" target=\"_blank\">Without Proof: The Unpersuasive Case Against Voter Identification</a>, which is more of a point by point refute of the Brennan Study.\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\">Two issues I said I\'d look into: the number of people without ID and the prevalence of voter fraud.</div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\"></div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\"></div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\">Did you know (at least as of 2008), Indiana had the \"most stringent voting requirements in the nation?\" I\'ll admit I didn\'t, but on that I trust the Indiana Voter Study (linked below (p. 2)). I also didn\'t know that our Voter ID law was upheld by SCOTUS in 2008.</div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\"><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crawford_v._Marion_County_Election_Board\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crawford_v._Marion_County_Election_Board</a></div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\"></div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\">For the record (from the Background section of the wikipedia link):</div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\">\"A 2005 Indiana law required all voters casting a ballot in person to present a United States or Indiana photo ID. Under the Indiana law, voters who do not have a photo ID may cast a provisional ballot. To have their votes counted, they must visit a designated government office within 10 days and bring a photo ID or sign a statement saying they cannot afford one.<sup id=\"cite_ref-0\"><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crawford_v._Marion_County_Election_Board#cite_note-0\">[1]</a>\"</sup></div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\"></div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\">Not sure if that tempers whether the law is draconian, but to me the last sentence does take some wind out of some of the horror stories\' sails. Regardless, the next paragraph really hones in on the complexity of the debate:</div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\">\"At trial, the plaintiffs were unable to produce any witnesses who claimed they were not able to meet the law\'s requirements. The defendants were likewise unable to present any evidence that the corruption purportedly motivating the law existed.</div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\"></div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\">Anyway, the study I found most referenced is this one by the Brennan Center (2006), \"Citizens for Proof\":</div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\"><a href=\"http://www.brennancenter.org/page/-/d/download_file_39242.pdf\">http://www.brennancenter.org/page/-/d/download_file_39242.pdf</a></div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\"></div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\">I must be missing the long version of this, but it was the one linked to in the article from them linked below. It\'s three pages and doesn\'t list the questions they asked (they list four questions and describe it as \"several\"?) , how they chose their 987 voting-age American citizen phone respondents (\"randomly\"???), or anything. Again, probably missing the long version, but couldn\'t find it.<!--more--></div>\r\n<div lang=\"x-western\">\r\n\r\nRecently, the Kansas Secretary of State, Kris W. Kobach, wrote this op-ed for the WSJ and referenced that study:\r\n<a href=\"http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748704816604576333650886790480.html\">http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748704816604576333650886790480.html</a>\r\nApparently, Indiana no longer has the \"most stringent voting requirements in the nation.\"\r\n\r\nBrennan Center parried with this:<a href=\"http://www.brennancenter.org/blog/archives/debunking_misinformation_on_photo_id/\">\r\nhttp://www.brennancenter.org/blog/archives/debunking_misinformation_on_photo_id/</a>\r\n\r\nThey link to lots of stuff (trying to get it through our thick heads). The second study they link supporting them is the Indiana Voter Study by  the Washington Institute for the Study of Ethnicity and Race<a href=\"http://depts.washington.edu/uwiser/documents/Indiana_voter.pdf\">\r\nhttp://depts.washington.edu/uwiser/documents/Indiana_voter.pdf</a>\r\nThis looks more like a real study. Tables, charts, citings, better description of methodology, etc.\r\n\r\nThat said, I get the gist, but could you please diagram this sentence from their conclusion? (copy and pasted, unedited)\r\np16:\r\n\"Our results suggest that the findings of our earlier work conducted in more broad areas (Barreto, Nuño and Sanchez 2007), as minority, low-income, and less educated Indiana residents are less likely to have access to valid photo identification.\"\r\n\r\nAll grammar aside, how about this statement?\r\n\"less likely to have access to valid photo identification\"\r\nOK, but how is their access to _acquire_ valid photo identification doing?\r\n\r\nI report (and editorialize), you decide.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Voter ID', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'voter-id', '', '', '2012-01-14 16:03:49', '2012-01-14 16:03:49', '', 0, 'http://ttmsoia.andyhill.us/?p=547', 0, 'post', '', 0),
